## 6) Provider Proof Compliance Integration

### 6.1 Receipt should reflect compliance clearly
Receipt must show:
- required photos minimum vs actual
- checklist completion percentage or pass/fail

### 6.2 Missing proof behavior
If proof is missing:
- Receipt shows “Attention needed” state
- Customer sees:
  - “We’re waiting on final proof from your provider.”
- Ops/Admin gets an alert hook (or queue item in Cockpit drilldown).

Do NOT hide incomplete receipts; show them with transparent status.

---

## 7) Recommendation & Upsell Rules (critical to keep premium feel)

## 7.1 Recommendation sources (priority order)
1. **Provider Level Recommendation** (from 3A completion flow)
2. **Courtesy Upgrade** performed level vs scheduled
3. **System inference** (signals + history) for adjacent add-ons, only if high confidence

## 7.2 Recommendation types supported (v1)
- **Level Upgrade** (same SKU)
- **Level Downgrade** (rare; only if provider explicitly recommends lower)
- **Adjacent Add-on** (related service)
- **Switch suggestion** (only if relevant and non-invasive; optional v1)

## 7.3 Frequency / throttling
- Never show more than 2 recommendations per receipt
- Do not repeat the same recommendation:
  - more than 2 times in 14 days
  - more than once per receipt type without new evidence
- If customer taps “Not interested,” suppress for 90 days.

## 7.4 Tone and copy
- Use “to keep the standard consistent” framing
- Avoid “upgrade now!” tone
- Show incremental value + incremental handles clearly

Examples:
- “We upgraded you today to meet Handled standards. To keep this result, Level 3 is recommended going forward (+5 handles).”
- “Level 2 includes outside only. Level 3 adds inside windows for +5 handles.”

---

## 8) Actions (One-tap changes) & Scheduling Rules

### 8.1 “Update going forward” behavior
When customer accepts a level change:
- Update the routine item’s `sku_level_id`
- Apply **next cycle** by default
- Show confirmation:
  - “Updated starting next cycle.”

### 8.2 “Add next time” behavior (adjacent add-on)
- Adds service as:
  - one-time next cycle add-on OR
  - routine item (depending on SKU type and default cadence)
- Must pass:
  - eligibility (coverage map)
  - capacity checks (if known)
- If capacity conflict:
  - show “We’ll schedule this for the next available cycle” (no scary errors)

### 8.3 “Keep current level” behavior
If customer declines a provider recommendation:
- record a decline event
- show calm warning:
  - “We’ll do our best within the scheduled time window.”

